User-Zero-Native (zun) | Performance Review Catalog
=============================================

Each item has:
- **Effort**: [S]mall / [M]edium / [L]arge (from original roadmap)
- **Impact**: estimated perf gain — S (minor), M (moderate), L (major)
- **Action**: + add / - remove/replace
- **Where**: specific files to modify
- **Agent-safe**: whether this can ship without breaking agents trained on vanilla Chrome
- **Status**: ACTIVE / SCRAPPED / CONDITIONAL

=============================================
## REVIEW DECISIONS
=============================================

### Fingerprinting policy
Speed-based fingerprinting (unnaturally low latency, low variance, machine-precise
inter-action timing) is explicitly acceptable and not a concern. Only structural
fingerprinting matters — missing JS execution artifacts, observable API differences,
cross-session state leaks.

### Agent compatibility constraint
Agents are trained on vanilla Chrome CDP behavior. Any change that alters what the
agent observes through CDP (Runtime.evaluate return shapes, event sequences, error
formats, session isolation) is not viable. Changes must be either transparent to the
agent or additive (new CDP domains/methods the agent can opt into after retraining).

### Scrapped items (3)
- **1.2** — Cannot replace Runtime.evaluate internals. Agents depend on RemoteObject
  shape (type/value/objectId), ExceptionDetails format, and V8 stack traces. Typed
  mojo methods can't produce these. Complex JS expressions (closures, chained calls)
  can't be mapped to pre-defined methods. The reduced alternative (optimize path to
  V8 without changing CDP contract) has much lower value for high complexity.
- **1.3** — Cannot bypass CDP as external protocol. Agents only speak CDP over
  WebSocket/pipe. A native mojo automation plane is unreachable from the agent. The
  reduced alternative (use native plane as CDP backend, short-circuiting known methods
  inside devtools_controller.cc) preserves the CDP contract but the implementation
  complexity of parsing CDP methods and routing them to mojo is comparable to the
  existing DevTools dispatch it replaces.
- **7.2** — Cannot implicitly share CefBrowserContext across sessions by policy match.
  A BrowserContext owns cookies, localStorage, IndexedDB, HTTP cache, service workers,
  and permissions. Two sessions with identical policies but different identities would
  corrupt each other's state silently. The reduced alternative (explicit opt-in via
  same session_name) is already how GetOrCreateForBrowserContext works today — there's
  nothing to build.

